Class imbalance.
One of the major advantages of our method is its ability to generate high-quality synthetic data for minor classes even with limited samples.
To further validate this advantage, we add only minor class samples to the original data, balancing the ratio of major to minor classes, then measure the classification performance of the machine learning model.
As shown in Table 2, adding minor class samples generated from our method leads to higher F1 scores and balanced accuracy on both Travel and Adult Income datasets, compared to when samples generated by other baselines are added.
In the Travel dataset, where the number of minor class samples is substantially low, baseline models, especially, CopulaGAN and CTGAN, demonstrate markedly low sensitivity, indicating their failure to accurately learn the minor class data distribution.
In contrast, our method demonstrates its efficacy in producing high-quality data for minor classes on the Travel dataset. Compared to the Original, it significantly improves the F1 score by 12.13%p, underscoring its superior performance of our approach.

Regression.
We also evaluate the enhancement in machine learning regression performance resulting from incorporating synthetic data into the original dataset, as shown in Table 3.
Defining groups within the California housing dataset, which consists solely of numerical values, is challenging. Here, we employ a simple grouping strategy that divides the dataset into two groups based on the median value.
With the addition of 30,000 samples, our method and baseline models exhibit a decline in performance.
Nonetheless, whereas the GReaT model shows an increase in MSE by 0.032, our method only has a marginal error increase of 0.010.
When synthetic data is added up to 30,000 samples, its influence on the data distribution becomes greater than that of the original data.
If the distribution of the generated data significantly differs from the original, adding a large amount of generated data can substantially alter the final data distribution, potentially leading to performance degradation of regression models.
However, the strategy of dividing data by the median and generating both of them can make the distribution of synthetic data more closely resemble that of the original data.
Therefore, synthetic data generated from our method, even in large volumes, maintains a distribution similar to the original, yielding better performance than data generated from other baseline models.
For further analysis, the results of machine learning models trained solely on synthetic data are provided in Appendix B.

Our results demonstrate that our method exhibits robust performance when applied with open-source LLMs across diverse datasets. Notably, in the Sick dataset, the Mistral model significantly outperforms all other methods including our method with GPT-3.5 in terms of balanced accuracy (BAL ACC). These results validate the broader applicability and general effectiveness of our methodology when applied with open-source LLMs.
We have successfully tested and validated our approach using open-source alternatives such as Mistral and Llama2. This demonstrates the flexibility of our method, ensuring it remains accessible and viable even for users without access to high-end cloud services.

Classification.
We conduct ablation study to assess the impact of the proposed strategies on classification performance.
This compares the performance when generated samples are added to the original data.
As shown in Table 7, the results indicate that removing the grouping method leads to a decrease in F1 scores within the Travel and Adult Income datasets, dropping from 70.18 to 50.98 and 70.17 to 68.56, respectively.
This underscores the effectiveness of Group-wise prompting in mitigating class imbalance, thereby enhancing the F1 score.
Due to the presence of repeating values, we adopts random word replacement on the Sick dataset.
For the Sick dataset, applying Group-wise prompting actually reduces performance. This decrease is attributed to the LLM stopping generation prematurely due to repetitive patterns such as ‘f,f,f,f,…’, leading to the generation of only the first group and failing to achieve balanced generation.
In this case, applying the random word replacement strategy enables balanced generation, resulting in a higher F1 score than applying CSV-style prompting sorely.
Using only descriptive sentences for generation significantly reduces the F1 score across all datasets compared to our method, particularly dropping to 0.00 for the Sick dataset. This drop to an F1 score of 0.00 indicates that the generated data is biased towards the major class, resulting in the classifier being trained not to predict the minor class.
This implies that generation based solely on descriptive sentences fails to reflect the original data distribution.

As shown in Table 8, in comparison with the sentence data format, the CSV-style input significantly reduces the number of input tokens from 1827 to 913 for Adult Income dataset, approximately half, demonstrating the superior token efficiency of the CSV-style over the descriptive sentence data format.
In terms of the generation success rate, the sentence format achieved 97%, while the CSV-style only reached 38%.
The higher success rate of the sentence format is attributed to the inclusion of additional conditions for generation, whereas the CSV style, generating immediate values, did not incorporate any conditions, leading to a lack of additional data generation.
However, when a group-wise prompting is applied to the CSV-style, the success rate increases from 38% to 94%.
Using only CSV-style prompting results in significantly low data generation efficiency.
Therefore, it is essential to apply group-wise prompting in conjunction to optimize both efficiency and the preservation of statistical relationships in the generated data.
